body:
For the follwing code, no matter what `f` is whether a `string`, `str` or `&str` it returns same error saying `error: format argument must be a string literal`.

I know it needs a string literal but I'm passing a string too, so why this is intentional?
What I could do If I want to rewrite a C code which contains `va_list`, what is same in Rust to implement `va_list`.

Currently, I'm trying to re-write this function, it looks easy in `C` as va_list allows variables to be passed as argument. But why Rust don't allow variable to passed as arguments to `format!` or `format_args!`.
I know there is `std::ffi::va_list`, but I want to do this in `Rust` way without using any foreign bindings or external dependency.

```
static void mpc_err_string_cat(char *buffer, int *pos, int *max, char const *fmt, ...) {
  int left = ((*max) - (*pos));
  va_list va;
  va_start(va, fmt);
  if (left < 0) { left = 0;}
  (*pos) += vsprintf(buffer + (*pos), fmt, va);
  va_end(va);
}
```

```
fn mpc_err_string_cat(buffer: &str, pos: &mut u8, max: &mut u8, fmt: &str, args: Arguments) {
    let mut left = *max - *pos;

    if left < 0 {
        left = 0;
    }

    let f = fmt.to_string();
    let f = format_args!(f, args);

    let mut buff = String::new();
    std::fmt::write(&mut buff, f).unwrap();
} 
```

```
--> src\lib.rs:613:18
    |
613 |     format_args!(f, args);
    |                  ^
    |
help: you might be missing a string literal to format with
    |
613 |     format_args!("{} {}", f, args);
    |                  ++++++++ 
```

